<HEADLINE>
WORLD VISION TAIWAN INVITES REVERENDS TO VISIT UGANDA
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  May 17 (CNA) 05/17/07  19:48:43 (By Ruth Wang)
</P>
<P>
The World Vision Taiwan (WVT), a Christian charity organization,
has invited several reverends of Christian churches to join a
delegation set to visit Uganda May 20-26 to acquire abetter
understanding of the east African country which has been struck
by serious famine and AIDS, a spokesman of the organization said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Joining  the delegation  are Rev.  Chang To-chien  of the
Presbyterian Church in Taiwan, Rev. Chang Mao-song of the
Hsintien Covenant Church, Rev. Tu Ming-ta of the Taichung Grace
Church and xxx Rev. Kenneth Troy Peterson of the Christian
Overseas Radio &amp; Television Inc., according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The reverends, led by WVT President Tu Ming-han, will help
deliver food to AIDS orphans and kids suffering from famine and
will visit donation recipient families and churches in Uganda,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
They will also learn about developments related to projects
currently being carried out in northern Uganda by the WVT, such
as land mine injury prevention and AIDS prevention projects, as
well as planned projects, including one related to public health
and another concerning water resources.
</P>
<P>
After the delegation returns to Taiwan, the WVT will hold two
seminars in June to introduce Uganda's situation to people in
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The organization will also hold three concerts in June to raise
funds for a "30 hour famine" campaign aimed at fighting hunger
which has entered its 18th year in Taiwan, the spokesman said,
adding that people who donate more than NT$300 to the campaign
will receive a ticket to one of the concerts.
</P>
